l0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14044/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14044/canvas/1/e16f8555-8c62-4b3a-b2b7-0acc58127555","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-01T14:58:50.350Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The arrangement and clothing of the characters in this scene suggest monotony and repetition. Reynolds and Alma are attempting to fit into high society and struggling to do so. It is only when they (eventually) let down their guard and reveal their inner desires (for control and domination) that their relationship can function and reach an equilibrium. Until then, it’s rooted in a sense of competition.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14044/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:69.35064935064922,132.46753246753235,1803.1168831168834,871.9480519480524"}}}]}]}]}